1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:00,566
Okay.

2
00:00:00,566 --> 00:00:01,300
In this lecture we're

3
00:00:01,300 --> 00:00:05,400
going to talk about graceful shutdown
and draining of your microservices.

4
00:00:05,433 --> 00:00:10,900
Now this is unique to distributed systems
because if I do a graceful shutdown

5
00:00:10,900 --> 00:00:14,666
in a normal application, I can handle
all that in the application itself.

6
00:00:15,166 --> 00:00:17,800
Like, hey,
I'm going to do a shutdown close

7
00:00:17,800 --> 00:00:21,300
on my database socket command,
you know, finish writing things out.

8
00:00:21,333 --> 00:00:22,766
It's pretty simple.

9
00:00:22,766 --> 00:00:28,600
In microservice architectures,
it can be a lot more complicated

10
00:00:28,600 --> 00:00:31,533
because I've got all of these processes
that are running.

11
00:00:31,533 --> 00:00:36,300
I need to shut them down, but
they may be partially processing things.

12
00:00:36,333 --> 00:00:38,500
So I need to have a strategy to do this.

13
00:00:38,500 --> 00:00:42,100
So that's what we mean
a graceful shutdown right.

14
00:00:42,766 --> 00:00:47,366
Instead of
even if someone did a kill or a Sigint

15
00:00:47,666 --> 00:00:50,766
on, one of your processes,
that's a microservice,

16
00:00:51,033 --> 00:00:55,000
you need to capture that and shut down
gracefully so you don't get corruption

17
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:55,700
in your database.

18
00:00:55,700 --> 00:00:58,233
That's one of the reasons
why we need to do that. Okay.

19
00:00:58,233 --> 00:01:02,500
There's lots of different reasons
why us, microservices could go down.

20
00:01:02,500 --> 00:01:05,500
We want to make sure
that if it does go down hard,

21
00:01:05,500 --> 00:01:08,933
that when we come back up
that we can handle things appropriately.

22
00:01:09,133 --> 00:01:12,133
And then also,
if there's any outstanding requests

23
00:01:12,300 --> 00:01:15,900
that we handle those,
appropriately as well, we want to drain

24
00:01:16,133 --> 00:01:20,533
any of the timeouts or ordering on
any upstream requests that are coming in.

25
00:01:20,800 --> 00:01:21,066
All right.

26
00:01:21,066 --> 00:01:23,500
So those are the sorts of things
we need to look at.

27
00:01:23,500 --> 00:01:26,933
And then we can talk about any, pitfalls,
with doing this. So

28
00:01:28,166 --> 00:01:30,833
here is the order of operations
on a graceful shutdown.

29
00:01:30,833 --> 00:01:36,433
First stop accepting new requests on that,
microservice.

30
00:01:36,466 --> 00:01:39,533
It's not just good enough
to just turn everything off

31
00:01:39,700 --> 00:01:43,900
because you still have some things
to finish working on.

32
00:01:44,200 --> 00:01:48,666
So that's the next thing you stop
new requests from coming in first,

33
00:01:49,566 --> 00:01:51,833
then you say, I'm going to finish

34
00:01:51,833 --> 00:01:55,433
any of the things
that are in in flight to finish.

35
00:01:55,433 --> 00:01:58,266
So maybe I have some requests
that are out there.

36
00:01:58,266 --> 00:02:01,633
They might be requests out there
for some underlying service.

37
00:02:01,933 --> 00:02:04,933
I need to wait for those to come back.
Okay.

38
00:02:05,200 --> 00:02:08,833
Then the next thing I need to do is
I need to deregister myself

39
00:02:09,233 --> 00:02:11,666
from the load balancer. Right.

40
00:02:11,666 --> 00:02:14,600
And you can either do that
before the in flight or after.

41
00:02:14,600 --> 00:02:16,566
It depends on
how you've architected things.

42
00:02:16,566 --> 00:02:18,233
But either way we'll do that.

43
00:02:18,233 --> 00:02:21,866
And then you want to enforce the maximum
drain timeout.

44
00:02:21,866 --> 00:02:22,200
Right.

45
00:02:22,200 --> 00:02:24,333
Because I can't sit there

46
00:02:24,333 --> 00:02:28,433
and try and drain for minutes or hours
when someone's asked me to do this.

47
00:02:28,433 --> 00:02:31,433
So you want to
you want to give a limit to it

48
00:02:31,866 --> 00:02:33,966
so that you do shut down,

49
00:02:33,966 --> 00:02:37,666
even if you lose some of the requests
that you may have outstanding.

50
00:02:38,600 --> 00:02:41,466
Make sure that you do close
any of your resources.

51
00:02:41,466 --> 00:02:44,800
Maybe you have a
socket open to a database or

52
00:02:46,100 --> 00:02:46,566
excuse me,

53
00:02:46,566 --> 00:02:49,566
to a file system or something like that.

54
00:02:49,666 --> 00:02:53,266
Make sure that you close those resources
appropriately.

55
00:02:53,566 --> 00:02:57,100
Also, omit
any logs and metrics for the shutdown.

56
00:02:57,133 --> 00:02:58,600
I'm shutting down.

57
00:02:58,600 --> 00:03:02,500
I'm finishing up X number of requests,
whatever the case may be.

58
00:03:02,500 --> 00:03:04,266
Right.

59
00:03:04,266 --> 00:03:08,433
And this will also protect
the user experience to the deploy.

60
00:03:08,433 --> 00:03:10,700
They're not going to have all this stuff
laying around sitting there.

61
00:03:10,700 --> 00:03:11,633
Right.

62
00:03:11,633 --> 00:03:14,766
Also remember
you got to watch out for partial rights

63
00:03:15,166 --> 00:03:17,866
because that could cause corruption
in your database

64
00:03:17,866 --> 00:03:21,333
or in your file system
wherever you're persisting.

65
00:03:21,500 --> 00:03:22,733
Data. Right.

66
00:03:22,733 --> 00:03:24,066
And then you want to keep

67
00:03:24,066 --> 00:03:27,600
all your background jobs
that you may have running consistent here.

68
00:03:28,066 --> 00:03:30,733
So that they're all kind of shutting down
the same way.

69
00:03:30,733 --> 00:03:32,433
All your microservices. Right.

70
00:03:33,400 --> 00:03:34,566
So this,

71
00:03:34,566 --> 00:03:38,200
this whole concept, we got to look
at all of these, different things.

72
00:03:38,433 --> 00:03:42,033
Another thing that you may want to look at
is reduce your timeouts for clients,

73
00:03:42,500 --> 00:03:45,633
so that they're not sitting,
waiting on a five minute timeout

74
00:03:46,100 --> 00:03:50,866
that, you know, hey, I didn't hear
from this thing in 15 seconds or 30s.

75
00:03:51,133 --> 00:03:52,933
And I know the right thing to do,

76
00:03:52,933 --> 00:03:55,933
and it enables safer rollbacks
and things like that.

77
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:00,000
Okay, so this is what it looks like
in sequence diagram.

78
00:04:00,033 --> 00:04:02,566
A request comes in to the load balancer.

79
00:04:02,566 --> 00:04:06,700
It's going to, route
the request to a service that's out there.

80
00:04:07,100 --> 00:04:11,966
And all of a sudden I get that,
I get the hey, you need to shut down.

81
00:04:12,266 --> 00:04:15,866
First thing I'm going to do, deregister
and then drain.

82
00:04:15,866 --> 00:04:16,566
Right?

83
00:04:16,566 --> 00:04:20,066
Which means I'm going to tell the load
balancer I'm not taking anything else.

84
00:04:20,333 --> 00:04:23,566
I'm going to stop any new requests
that do, sneak in

85
00:04:23,566 --> 00:04:26,133
and not do those and reject them
right away.

86
00:04:26,133 --> 00:04:28,866
And then I'm going to finish
all my in-flight work,

87
00:04:28,866 --> 00:04:32,533
and then I'm going to tell the load
balancer I'm completely done

88
00:04:32,533 --> 00:04:33,466
de registering.

89
00:04:33,466 --> 00:04:37,666
I finish my drain
and I'm going to shut down that instance.

90
00:04:38,633 --> 00:04:40,733
It's pretty straightforward.

91
00:04:40,733 --> 00:04:41,833
Okay.

92
00:04:41,833 --> 00:04:47,800
So you want to make sure that you are
separating readiness from liveness probes.

93
00:04:47,800 --> 00:04:52,033
So so
I may still want to give a health update

94
00:04:52,033 --> 00:04:55,033
and say the health update maybe,

95
00:04:55,266 --> 00:04:58,300
I'm actually, shutting down right now.

96
00:04:58,300 --> 00:05:00,166
That might be a good health update.

97
00:05:00,166 --> 00:05:03,566
So if someone's, hitting you
for your health check,

98
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:07,333
you should return something and say,
hey, I'm.

99
00:05:07,600 --> 00:05:08,966
I'm shutting down.

100
00:05:08,966 --> 00:05:11,966
That's a good thing to give to, like,
a load balancer

101
00:05:12,033 --> 00:05:15,700
or, an external observer
to see what's going on

102
00:05:15,700 --> 00:05:18,100
so that that makes it, important.

103
00:05:18,100 --> 00:05:23,066
Also, make sure that all your handlers
and any retries are independent,

104
00:05:23,066 --> 00:05:27,066
which means that if they run
the same command multiple times,

105
00:05:27,066 --> 00:05:30,600
my state does not change on the back
end, right?

106
00:05:30,933 --> 00:05:34,866
That I'm guaranteed
the I'm guaranteed the same state

107
00:05:34,866 --> 00:05:37,866
regardless of how many times
I call the same thing right?

108
00:05:38,300 --> 00:05:38,700
And then,

109
00:05:40,066 --> 00:05:40,866
make sure that

110
00:05:40,866 --> 00:05:44,500
you are closing
all the shared resources last.

111
00:05:44,800 --> 00:05:46,000
So I got everything done.

112
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:49,166
Now I can close all the
all those resources that I have in there.

113
00:05:49,333 --> 00:05:50,500
Okay. All right.

114
00:05:50,500 --> 00:05:53,500
So here's a simple example in go,

115
00:05:53,800 --> 00:05:56,800
where I can see,

116
00:05:57,400 --> 00:06:01,333
un listing for this
sig term or sig int right.

117
00:06:01,333 --> 00:06:04,700
Someone does it forces a shut down.

118
00:06:05,166 --> 00:06:08,166
I call server shutdown with a timeout,

119
00:06:08,466 --> 00:06:11,466
and then I stop
any new requests immediately.

120
00:06:11,800 --> 00:06:14,633
And then I let in-flight work finish.

