00:08:28,066 --> 00:08:28,400
All right.

166
00:08:28,400 --> 00:08:29,700
Architectural trade offs.

167
00:08:29,700 --> 00:08:33,400
So this is a big one. Reliability.

168
00:08:33,400 --> 00:08:36,400
This is this is an important one because,

169
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:40,700
I'm reducing the dropped requests.

170
00:08:40,700 --> 00:08:43,700
Even though there could be
a timeout still. So

171
00:08:44,800 --> 00:08:47,700
my reliability could be a little bit
questionable.

172
00:08:47,700 --> 00:08:49,766
Latency is an issue here

173
00:08:49,766 --> 00:08:53,300
because I'm doing a longer drain windows
for slower rollouts.

174
00:08:53,766 --> 00:08:57,000
So if I'm shutting something down,
I could take a little bit longer

175
00:08:57,133 --> 00:09:00,133
to finish shutting that down
before I spin up the new instance.

176
00:09:00,133 --> 00:09:00,900
Right.

177
00:09:00,900 --> 00:09:04,300
Cost could be an issue
because there's extra capacity

178
00:09:04,300 --> 00:09:10,200
for staying online during a drain,
but maybe not to too much scalability.

179
00:09:10,533 --> 00:09:13,300
Safe scaling in leads to,

180
00:09:13,300 --> 00:09:16,300
my load balancing coordination.

181
00:09:16,466 --> 00:09:22,133
As I got, maybe I have five instances
running of a certain microservice.

182
00:09:22,400 --> 00:09:25,733
And I called shut down on two of them,
and they take a couple of minutes

183
00:09:25,733 --> 00:09:27,066
to shut down.

184
00:09:27,066 --> 00:09:31,000
I'm still holding on to to those, slots,
which means I'm

185
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:35,300
only accepting three at that time,
while the other two are shutting down.

186
00:09:35,300 --> 00:09:38,900
When they're completely shut down,
the new ones will spin up in their places.

187
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:42,366
So I'm losing some scalability
for a short period of time.

188
00:09:42,666 --> 00:09:45,166
And then also complexity
is an issue with these,

189
00:09:46,500 --> 00:09:47,900
with these shutdowns.

190
00:09:47,900 --> 00:09:48,266
Right.

191
00:09:48,266 --> 00:09:52,833
I have to handle, signal handling,
which is kind of a pain.

192
00:09:52,833 --> 00:09:56,900
Sometimes I need to handle order
ordering of finishing up requests

193
00:09:56,900 --> 00:09:57,900
and all those sorts of things.

194
00:09:57,900 --> 00:10:00,900
So you got, 
these are some architectural trade offs,

195
00:10:01,166 --> 00:10:04,666
but the benefits are pretty substantial,

196
00:10:04,866 --> 00:10:08,366
which is, consistency in my data
on the back end.

197
00:10:08,366 --> 00:10:10,300
And things like that. Right.

198
00:10:10,300 --> 00:10:11,066
All right.

199
00:10:11,066 --> 00:10:13,566
Some pitfalls to, to watch out for.

200
00:10:13,566 --> 00:10:16,566
Don't forget to deregister
from the load balancer.

201
00:10:16,933 --> 00:10:18,733
Right. This instance is running.

202
00:10:18,733 --> 00:10:22,000
I need to say I'm going to deregister
because I don't want any more instance.

203
00:10:22,133 --> 00:10:24,900
I don't want any more stuff
coming to me. Right.

204
00:10:24,900 --> 00:10:29,133
Make sure that your drain timeout
is not too short

205
00:10:29,666 --> 00:10:33,200
or you're going to consistently get bad.

206
00:10:34,133 --> 00:10:36,400
State out of out of the back end of it.

207
00:10:36,400 --> 00:10:40,566
Make sure that you close all those database connections before responses complete.

208
00:10:41,633 --> 00:10:43,333
Make sure
that you don't before they're complete,

209
00:10:43,333 --> 00:10:45,000
but make sure that you close them
at the end.

210
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:46,966
Otherwise you end up with open sockets.

211
00:10:46,966 --> 00:10:49,966
You can run out of sockets
on your operating system.

212
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:50,566
All right.

213
00:10:50,566 --> 00:10:54,200
And make sure you're not ignoring
any background jobs that are spun up,

214
00:10:54,200 --> 00:10:58,066
or you end up with a bunch
of zombie processes on the back end,

215
00:10:58,566 --> 00:11:02,200
which could, pollute your process space
and cause

216
00:11:02,200 --> 00:11:05,966
a lot of issues
on using resources that you may not have.

217
00:11:06,466 --> 00:11:07,333
All right.

218
00:11:07,333 --> 00:11:13,100
So remember, drain your traffic,
finish the work, and shutdown cleanly.

219
00:11:13,100 --> 00:11:15,733
Those those are the key
things on shutdown and drain.
